# Responses of East Francia and England to Viking Attacks: A Detailed Report

The Viking Age, spanning roughly from the late 8th century to the early 11th century, was marked by extensive raids, invasions, and settlements by Norse seafarers across Europe. Both East Francia (a precursor to modern Germany) and England faced significant challenges from Viking incursions. Their responses to these threats were multifaceted, involving military, political, and diplomatic strategies that shaped the future of these regions. This report provides a comprehensive analysis of how East Francia and England responded to Viking attacks, drawing from multiple historical sources to present an in-depth, structured, and objective account.

---

## Early Viking Attacks and Context

The Vikings, originating from modern-day Sweden, Denmark, and Norway, were skilled sailors and warriors who launched sudden and devastating raids on coastal and riverine settlements. Their longships allowed them to navigate both open seas and shallow rivers, making many areas vulnerable.

- The first notable Viking raid on England was the attack on the monastery of Lindisfarne in 793 AD, where monks were killed or enslaved, and the monastery was plundered and burned ([Penfield.edu](https://www.penfield.edu/webpages/jgiotto/onlinetextbook.cfm?subpage=1501196)).
- Within five years, Viking raids extended to the northern coast of France, targeting wealthy and poorly defended areas ([CourseHero](https://www.coursehero.com/tutors-problems/World-History/35153180-How-did-England-and-East-Francia-respond-to-Viking-attacks/)).

---

## East Francia’s Response to Viking Attacks

### Political and Military Context

East Francia emerged from the division of the Carolingian Empire after the death of Louis the Pious and the Treaty of Verdun in 843. The kingdom, ruled by Louis the German, faced internal strife and external threats, including Viking raids.

### Defensive Measures

- **Fortification Network:** Charlemagne, the Frankish monarch before the division, had already initiated defensive measures by building a network of fortresses along vulnerable coastlines to deter Viking raids ([CourseHero](https://www.coursehero.com/tutors-problems/World-History/35153180-How-did-England-and-East-Francia-respond-to-Viking-attacks/)).
- **Military Leadership:** Louis the German proved to be a potent military commander. After the Vikings sacked Hamburg in 845, he successfully repelled further serious Viking incursions for approximately 30 years ([WarHistoryOnline](https://www.warhistoryonline.com/medieval/8-brutal-conflicts-franks-vikings.html)).

### Tactical Engagements

- The Franks relied heavily on their cavalry, the predecessors of medieval knights, who were armored shock troops capable of decisive battlefield maneuvers. This military advantage was crucial in confronting Viking raiders, who were primarily infantry-based and relied on surprise and mobility ([WarHistoryOnline](https://www.warhistoryonline.com/medieval/8-brutal-conflicts-franks-vikings.html)).
- Despite this, the Vikings conducted successful raids on key cities such as Paris (sacked twice in 856 and 857) and other towns along the Seine valley. The Vikings used both longboats and horses to penetrate deep into Frankish territory ([WarHistoryOnline](https://www.warhistoryonline.com/medieval/8-brutal-conflicts-franks-vikings.html)).

### Diplomatic and Political Outcomes

- The fragmentation of the Frankish Empire into East, West, and Middle Francia created vulnerabilities that the Vikings exploited.
- Over time, Viking leaders such as Rollo were granted land (notably in northern France, leading to the establishment of Normandy in 911) in exchange for their acknowledgment of Frankish sovereignty, effectively integrating some Viking groups into the Frankish political system ([CourseHero](https://www.coursehero.com/tutors-problems/World-History/35153180-How-did-England-and-East-Francia-respond-to-Viking-attacks/)).

