## England’s Response to Viking Attacks

### Initial Viking Incursions

- The Vikings began raiding England with the attack on Lindisfarne in 793, followed by a series of raids on Northumbria, East Anglia, Kent, and Wessex throughout the 9th century ([Britannica](https://www.britannica.com/place/United-Kingdom/The-period-of-the-Scandinavian-invasions)).
- Danish Vikings launched a large-scale invasion in 865 AD, led by Ivar the Boneless and Halfdan, sons of the legendary Ragnar Lodbrok. They quickly captured York in 866 and established control over Northumbria and East Anglia ([About-History](https://about-history.com/viking-conquest-in-england/)).

### Military Resistance and Political Strategies

- **King Alfred the Great’s Campaigns:** Alfred the Great, king of Wessex, emerged as the principal defender against the Viking incursions. In 878, he won a decisive victory at the Battle of Edington, which led to a treaty with the Vikings. This treaty established the Danelaw, a region in northern and eastern England where Danish law prevailed ([CourseHero](https://www.coursehero.com/tutors-problems/World-History/35153180-How-did-England-and-East-Francia-respond-to-Viking-attacks/)).
- Alfred also promoted the Christianization of Viking leaders, notably overseeing the baptism of the Viking chieftain Guthrum, which helped stabilize relations ([CourseHero](https://www.coursehero.com/tutors-problems/World-History/35153180-How-did-England-and-East-Francia-respond-to-Viking-attacks/)).

### Defensive Innovations

- Alfred developed a national defense system that included a network of fortified towns (burhs) and a standing army.
- He also established a navy to counter Viking longships, which were the primary means of Viking raids ([About-History](https://about-history.com/viking-conquest-in-england/)).

### Political and Social Impact

- The Danelaw remained a semi-autonomous region under Danish law, with its own social and political structures, even as the Anglo-Saxon kings regained control over southern England ([About-History](https://about-history.com/viking-conquest-in-england/)).
- The English kings, particularly Ethelred II, resorted to paying Danegeld (a tax to pay off Viking raiders) starting in 991, which was the first universal tax recorded in Britain. However, this was only a temporary measure and did not prevent further raids ([About-History](https://about-history.com/viking-conquest-in-england/)).

### Later Viking Invasions and Political Collapse

- In the late 10th and early 11th centuries, renewed Danish raids intensified. King Ethelred II organized mass pogroms against Danes living in England in 1002, but this failed to stop the Viking threat ([About-History](https://about-history.com/viking-conquest-in-england/)).
- The Danish king Sven Forkbeard led a successful invasion in 1013, forcing Ethelred II to flee to Normandy. After Sven's death in 1014, Ethelred briefly regained power, but by 1016, the Danish conquest was effectively complete under Cnut the Great ([England's Northeast](https://englandsnortheast.co.uk/viking-age-northumbria/)).

